## 11. Potential Questions & Answers

**Q: Why MongoDB and not SQL?**
> A: The data has nested structures (shift results contain per-server arrays). MongoDB's document model handles this naturally without complex joins. Also, MongoDB scales horizontally for real-world IoT data volumes.

**Q: Why two anomaly detection models instead of one?**
> A: Isolation Forest and DBSCAN detect different types of anomalies. IF is good at finding isolated outliers (global anomalies), while DBSCAN excels at finding points in sparse regions (local anomalies). Using both gives broader coverage.

**Q: What is the emission factor 0.82?**
> A: It represents 0.82 kg CO₂ per kWh — a realistic average grid carbon intensity. In production, this would come from a real-time carbon intensity API (like WattTime or Electricity Maps).

**Q: Is the workload shifting actually moving workloads?**
> A: No, it's a **simulation**. It calculates hypothetical savings if flexible workloads were rescheduled. In production, this would integrate with a job scheduler (like Kubernetes CronJobs) to actually defer batch work.

**Q: How are "flexible" servers identified?**
> A: Using Coefficient of Variation (CV < 0.2 means steady power, likely batch workloads) and whether their peak usage falls during red hours. Interactive servers have high variability, so they're marked inflexible.

**Q: What does the z-score feature represent?**
> A: It measures how many standard deviations a reading is from the server's 1-hour rolling average. A z-score of 3 means the reading is 3 standard deviations away — very unusual.

